      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "MMS or equivalent analytical verification demonstrating correct order-of-accuracy for all active physics modules.",
      "rationale": "MMS verification confirmed second-order spatial convergence for the SST k-omega turbulence model and the power-law hemolysis scalar transport equation. Results documented in VR-03. No anomalous convergence behaviour observed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "GCI < 5 % for the primary QoI (RHI) at all five COU operating points.",
      "rationale": "Three-level Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI values of 0.8–2.3 % for RHI across all operating points, as documented in VR-01. The medium mesh (11.7 M cells) was selected for production runs, providing an adequate balance of accuracy and computational cost. Discretisation error is bounded well within acceptance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation must correspond to the COU operating envelope; deviations must be documented and justified.",
      "rationale": "FDA interlaboratory experiments were conducted at 2500 rpm and 3500 rpm with porcine blood at 37 °C, matching two of the five COU operating points directly. The remaining three points are interpolated within the validated operating envelope. Fluid temperature and hematocrit deviations from clinical values are within the ranges characterised by the UQ campaign (VR-04). Test condition correspondence is adequate for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted NIH within one experimental standard deviation at ≥ 4 of 5 operating points; over-predictions must be conservative relative to the acceptance criterion.",
      "rationale": "CFD NIH predictions satisfy the acceptance criterion at 4 of 5 operating points. The single non-conforming point exhibits a 7 % conservative over-prediction, confirmed by the PCE-based 90 % prediction interval (VR-02). The over-prediction direction is conservative for worst-case identification, consistent with the COU intent."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The primary QoI (RHI) must be directly linked to the regulatory acceptance criterion and clinically relevant hemolysis metric.",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index RHI is defined as the ratio of device NIH to predicate NIH. It directly maps to the FDA acceptance criterion (RHI < 1) and is the standard metric in 510(k) submissions for blood-contacting devices. The QoI is fully relevant to the COU decision."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must use the same model form, hemolysis constitutive law, and boundary condition strategy as the COU simulations.",
      "rationale": "Validation simulations used identical solver settings, turbulence model, hemolysis power-law constants, and boundary condition prescription as the COU production runs. The only difference is pump geometry (FDA generic vs. device-specific); geometric sensitivity was characterised in the UQ campaign (VR-04) and found to contribute < 4 % of RHI variance. Validation relevance is confirmed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
